# `final` Keyword in Java

`final` means **cannot be changed**.
It can be used with:
1. Variable
2. Method
3. Class

---

## 1. Final Variable

```java
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        final int age = 21;
        // age = 22;  // Error
        System.out.println(age);
    }
}
```

### Output
```
21
```

Once assigned, the value cannot be changed.

---

## 2. Final Method

```java
class Father {
    final void property() {
        System.out.println("Father's property");
    }
}

class Son extends Father {
    // void property() { }  // Error
}
```

A `final` method **cannot be overridden** by a child class.

---

## 3. Final Class

```java
final class Father {
}

class Son extends Father { } // Error
```

A `final` class **cannot be inherited**.

---

## Simple Example

```java
final class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Eating");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Animal a = new Animal();
        a.eat();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Eating
```

---

## Easy Memory Trick

```
final variable → value cannot change
final method   → cannot override
final class    → cannot inherit
```

---

## Interview Definition

**The `final` keyword is used to restrict modification. A final variable cannot be reassigned, a final method cannot be overridden, and a final class cannot be extended.** 🚀









# `super` Keyword in Java

`super` refers to the parent class object.
It is mainly used to:

1. Access parent class variables
2. Access parent class methods
3. Call parent class constructor

---

## 1. Access Parent Class Method

```java
class Father {
    void property() {
        System.out.println("Father's property");
    }
}

class Son extends Father {
    void show() {
        super.property();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Son s = new Son();
        s.show();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Father's property
```

---

## 2. Access Parent Class Variable

```java
class Father {
    int money = 10000;
}

class Son extends Father {
    int money = 5000;

    void display() {
        System.out.println(super.money);
        System.out.println(money);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Son s = new Son();
        s.display();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
10000
5000
```

- `super.money` → Parent's variable
- `money` → Child's variable

---

## 3. Call Parent Constructor

```java
class Father {
    Father() {
        System.out.println("Father Constructor");
    }
}

class Son extends Father {
    Son() {
        super();
        System.out.println("Son Constructor");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Son s = new Son();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Father Constructor
Son Constructor
```

---

## Complete Example

```java
class Father {
    int money = 10000;

    Father() {
        System.out.println("Father Constructor");
    }

    void property() {
        System.out.println("Father's Property");
    }
}

class Son extends Father {
    int money = 5000;

    Son() {
        super();
        System.out.println("Son Constructor");
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Father Money = " + super.money);
        System.out.println("Son Money = " + money);
        super.property();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Son s = new Son();
        s.display();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Father Constructor
Son Constructor
Father Money = 10000
Son Money = 5000
Father's Property
```

---

## Easy Memory Trick

```
super.variable  → Parent variable
super.method()  → Parent method
super()         → Parent constructor
```

---

## Interview Definition

**The `super` keyword is used to refer to the immediate parent class object. It can be used to access parent class variables, methods, and constructors.** 🚀





# `this` Keyword in Java

`this` refers to the **current object**.
It is mainly used to:
1. Access current class variables
2. Call current class methods
3. Call current class constructor

---

## 1. Access Current Class Variable

```java
class Student {
    String name;

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(this.name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student("Jayasri");
        s.display();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Jayasri
```

### Why `this`?

```java
Student(String name) {
    this.name = name;
}
```

- `this.name` → instance variable
- `name` → constructor parameter

---

## 2. Call Current Class Method

```java
class Student {
    void study() {
        System.out.println("Studying");
    }

    void display() {
        this.study();
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
        s.display();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Studying
```

---

## 3. Call Current Class Constructor

```java
class Student {
    Student() {
        this("Jayasri");
        System.out.println("Default Constructor");
    }

    Student(String name) {
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Jayasri
Default Constructor
```

---

## Complete Example

```java
class Student {
    String name;

    Student() {
        this("Jayasri");
    }

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void show() {
        this.display();
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println(this.name);
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
        s.show();
    }
}
```

### Output
```
Jayasri
```

---

## `this` vs `super`

| `this`         | `super`        |
| -------------- | -------------- |
| Current object | Parent object  |
| `this.name`    | `super.name`   |
| `this.show()`  | `super.show()` |
| `this()`       | `super()`      |

---

## Easy Memory Trick

```
this.variable → Current class variable
this.method() → Current class method
this()        → Current class constructor
```

---

## Interview Definition

**The `this` keyword refers to the current object of a class. It is used to access current class variables, methods, and constructors.** 🚀




